'''Rebecca Tushnet''' (born April 4, 1973) is the inaugural [[Frank Stanton (executive)|Frank Stanton]] Professor of First Amendment Law at [[Harvard Law School]] and an American [[copyright law|copyright]], [[trademark law|trademark]], [[First Amendment]], and [[false advertising]] legal scholar.  In addition to her general scholarship, Tushnet is known for her [[fanfiction]]-related scholarship<ref>{{cite radio | title=Fan Fiction and the Law | work=[[On the Media]] | author=Bob Garfield | url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/274585-fan-fiction-and-law/ | date=8 March 2013 | publisher=[[WNYC]]}}</ref> and her legal advocacy work for the [[Organization for Transformative Works]], a nonprofit [[fandom]]-related project that supports fanworks (such as [[fanfiction]]) through preservation and advocacy.<ref>[http://transformativeworks.org/projects/legal "Legal Advocacy"], Organization for Transformative Works. (Last visited April 28, 2014).</ref><ref>[[Nick Gillespie]] & [[Joshua Swain]], [http://reason.com/blog/2012/07/20/fan-fiction-vs-copyright-qa-with-rebecca "Fan Fiction vs. Copyright - Q&A with Rebecca Tushnet"], ''Reason Magazine'', July 20, 2012.</ref>

Tushnet was a [[policy debate|policy debater]] at Harvard, getting to finals of the [[National Debate Tournament]] in 1992 and 1995<ref>{{cite web|url=https://groups.wfu.edu/NDT/HistoricalLists/winners.html}}</ref>, she received an A.B. from Harvard University in 1995, and earned her J.D. from [[Yale Law School]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Rebecca L. Tushnet|url=https://www.law.georgetown.edu/faculty/tushnet-rebecca-l.cfm|website=Georgetown Law|publisher=Georgetown University|accessdate=30 July 2017}}</ref> in 1998.<ref name="uccv">[http://www.law.uchicago.edu/node/11174/cv Tushnet CV], University of Chicago (last visited April 28, 2014).</ref>
Tushnet served as a law clerk to Judge [[Edward R. Becker]] of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit]] and later for Justice [[David Souter]] of the [[United States Supreme Court]]. from 1999 to 2000. [[Edward R. Becker]] (1998–99)<ref name="uccv" /> She practiced at [[Debevoise & Plimpton]]. Tushnet then entered teaching, first at NYU School of Law (2002–04),<ref name="uccv" /> then at [[Georgetown University Law Center]] (2004–16),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.georgetown.edu/faculty/tushnet-rebecca-l.cfm|title=Profile Rebecca Tushnet — Georgetown Law|website=www.law.georgetown.edu|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> and most recently at [[Harvard Law School]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://today.law.harvard.edu/rebecca-tushnet-joins-harvard-law-faculty-professor/|title=Rebecca Tushnet joins Harvard Law faculty as Professor of First Amendment Law - Harvard Law Today|newspaper=Harvard Law Today|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> In practice, Tushnet has represented fans in copyright and trademark disputes with rightsholders.<ref>NPR, [https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=92577677 "Fan Fiction Writers Face Nonfiction Legal Hurdles"], July 16, 2008.</ref>

Her father is [[Mark Tushnet]] and her mother is Elizabeth Alexander, who directs the National Prison Project of the [[American Civil Liberties Union]].<ref name="nytimes1">https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/05/us/05beliefs.html</ref> Her sister [[Eve Tushnet]] is a lesbian Catholic author and blogger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://americamagazine.org/content/all-things/gay-and-catholic-interview-author-eve-tushnet |title='Gay and Catholic': An Interview with Author Eve Tushnet |publisher=America Magazine |date= |accessdate=2015-03-21}}</ref>

== Selected scholarship and casebooks ==

; Articles
* "Worth a Thousand Words: The Images of Copyright Law", 125 Harv. L. Rev. 683 (2012)
* "Gone in 60 Milliseconds: Trademark Law and Cognitive Science", 86 Texas L. Rev. 507 (2008)
* "Legal Fictions: Copyright, Fan Fiction, and a New Common Law", 17 ''[[Loy. L.A. Ent. L.J.]]'' 651 (1997)
* "Copy This Essay: How Fair Use Doctrine Harms Free Speech and How Copying Serves It", 114 ''[[Yale L.J.]]'' 535 (2004)
* "Copyright as a Model for Free Speech Law: What Copyright Has in Common with Anti-Pornography Laws, Campaign Finance Reform, and Telecommunications Regulation" 42 ''[[B.C. L. Rev.]]'' 1 (2000)

; Casebooks
* ''[http://www.advertisinglawbook.com/ Advertising & Marketing Law: Cases & Materials]'' (2014 ed.), with [[Eric Goldman]] (the first casebook on this topic)<ref>{{Citation | url = https://gum.co/zPsX | publisher = self-published | title = Advertising & Marketing Law: Cases & Materials| date = July 2012}}.</ref>

== Awards ==
* 1997 Nathan Burkan Prize for best paper in the field of copyright ("Legal Fictions")
* The Copyright Society of the USA awarded her the 2014 Seton Award for [http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2264277 Performance Anxiety: Copyright Embodied and Disembodied], 60 J. Copyright Soc’y U.S.A. 209 (2013)<ref>http://www.csusa.org/news/177866/Rebecca-Tushnet-Named-2014-Seton-Award-Winner.htm</ref>
* [https://www.publicknowledge.org/events/12th-annual-ip3-awards 2015 recipient of Public Knowledge’s IP3 Award] in the area of intellectual property
* In 2016, her blog was inducted into the ABA Journal's "Blawg 100 Hall of Fame."<ref>http://www.abajournal.com/magazine/article/2013_blawg_100_hall_of_fame</ref>

